[5] Liberia: alert -- 49 new Ebola cases in Grand Cape Mount
Date: Mon 29 Dec 2014
Source: Front Page Africa [edited]
http://www.frontpageafricaonline.com/index.php/health-sci/4133-alarm-49-new-ebola-cases-in-cape-mount-travelers-warned


The Incident Management System, an arm of the Liberian government, and partners responsible for the containment of the Ebola virus disease in the country [Liberia] have stated that the disease is growing at an alarming rate in Grand Cape Mount County. Speaking to journalists at the Incident Command Center on [Sun 28 Dec 2014], the head of Liberia's Ebola response, Mr Tolbert Nyenswah said a total of 49 cases have been reported in the area and this hike in the number of cases is due to failure to follow health procedures laid out by the government of Liberia. He said the county now joins Montserrado as the 2 counties with the most Ebola cases.

"In the past 25 days, 1-25 Dec 2014, 49 cases have been reported, 27 confirmed, 9 probable, and 13 cases suspected. He said the disease continues to spread [due to] a high level of complacency on the part of community dwellers in gross disregard for the preventative measures that have been laid out by the Ministry of health. Mr Nyenswah [pointed to] migration of suspected and probable cases within and out of the county, [and] continuous denial by community dwellers that people are dying from Ebola. He said despite such denial the bodies that are being tested turn out to be Ebola positive.

Mr Nyenswah said traditional and cultural practices are still entrenched and people are refusing to stop touching or bathing dead bodies. He said in many cases due to denial, some even hide the sick in their homes [to care] for them and when they eventually die, the family arranges secret burials for their dead relatives.

He said people are no longer washing hands with chlorinated water or [using] sanitizers or other items. He said in the wake of this grave health alert, the government and its partners are holding an emergency meeting in Sinje, Grand Cape Mount County, that coincides with the opening of the 1st Ebola Treatment Unit of 100-bed in Grand Cape Mount County.

He said the government is installing an Ebola lab to test all cases swiftly and [mobilizing] all partners to move into the county to give support. The assistant Minister for Health of Liberia said there has to be drastic behavioral change if the county must reverse its current Ebola numbers... -- more

[Byline: Wade CL Williams]

