See also: Plowright RK, Eby P, Hudson PJ, et al: Ecological dynamics of emerging bat virus spillover. Proc Biol Sci. 2015 Jan 7;282(1798). pii: 20142124; http://rspb.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/282/1798/20142124.long, and Olival KJ, Hayman DT: Filoviruses in bats: current knowledge and future directions. Viruses. 2014; 6(4): 1759-88. doi: 10.3390/v6041759. Review; http://www.mdpi.com/1999-4915/6/4/1759/htm

And see http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2014/12/141230-ebola-virus-origin-insect-bats-meliandou-reservoir-host for additional photos and a map.

The natural reservoir host of Ebola virus, a zoonosis, has not yet been definitively identified in spite of efforts on the part of numerous investigative teams. This study is intriguing, but more field work must be done to confirm suspicion of this bat as the primary host of the ongoing outbreak. - Mod.LK]

